[{"location":"pages/t001_simple_dynamics/","page":"1 Simple Dynamics","title":"1 Simple Dynamics","text":"EditURL = \"https://github.com/SciQuant/Tutorials/blob/master/src/simple_dynamics.jl\"","category":"page"},{"location":"pages/t001_simple_dynamics/#Tutorial-1:-Simple-Dynamics","page":"1 Simple Dynamics","title":"Tutorial 1: Simple Dynamics","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"pages/t001_simple_dynamics/","page":"1 Simple Dynamics","title":"1 Simple Dynamics","text":"(Image: ) (Image: )","category":"page"},{"location":"pages/t001_simple_dynamics/","page":"1 Simple Dynamics","title":"1 Simple Dynamics","text":"In this tutorial, you will learn:","category":"page"},{"location":"pages/t001_simple_dynamics/","page":"1 Simple Dynamics","title":"1 Simple Dynamics","text":"How to declare dynamics with arbitrary coefficients\nHow to declare dynamics with known coefficients\nHow to declare dynamical systems","category":"page"},{"location":"pages/t001_simple_dynamics/#Introduction","page":"1 Simple Dynamics","title":"Introduction","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"pages/t001_simple_dynamics/","page":"1 Simple Dynamics","title":"1 Simple Dynamics","text":"In UniversalDynamics a dynamics represents continuous time, D-dimensional Ito Systems of Stochastic Differential Equations (SDEs) in a time span mathbbI = leftt_0 T right:","category":"page"},{"location":"pages/t001_simple_dynamics/","page":"1 Simple Dynamics","title":"1 Simple Dynamics","text":"dvecu(t) = f(t vecu(t)) cdot dt + g(t vecu(t)) cdot dvecW(t) quad vecu(t_0) = vecu_0","category":"page"},{"location":"pages/t001_simple_dynamics/","page":"1 Simple Dynamics","title":"1 Simple Dynamics","text":"with drift coefficient f colon mathbbI times mathbbR^D rightarrow mathbbR^D, diffusion coefficient g colon mathbbI times mathbbR^D rightarrow mathbbR^D times M, M-dimensional driving Wiener correlated or uncorrelated process vecW(t) and initial condition vecu_0.","category":"page"},{"location":"pages/t001_simple_dynamics/","page":"1 Simple Dynamics","title":"1 Simple Dynamics","text":"The library represents dynamics by means of two main types, SystemDynamics and ModelDynamics. The first case refers to SDEs with arbitrary coefficients while the second case is a supertype for dynamics with known coefficients that are already implemented in the library.","category":"page"},{"location":"pages/t001_simple_dynamics/","page":"1 Simple Dynamics","title":"1 Simple Dynamics","text":"Finally, as discussed in the documentation, the general expression of a dynamics can be reduced depending on the noise type.","category":"page"},{"location":"pages/t001_simple_dynamics/","page":"1 Simple Dynamics","title":"1 Simple Dynamics","text":"# Setup","category":"page"},{"location":"pages/t001_simple_dynamics/","page":"1 Simple Dynamics","title":"1 Simple Dynamics","text":"The first step is to load the library:","category":"page"},{"location":"pages/t001_simple_dynamics/","page":"1 Simple Dynamics","title":"1 Simple Dynamics","text":"using UniversalDynamics\n\n# System Dynamics","category":"page"},{"location":"pages/t001_simple_dynamics/","page":"1 Simple Dynamics","title":"1 Simple Dynamics","text":"A System of Stochastic Differential Equations is declared by its initial condition, initial time, noise type and noise correlations, for example:","category":"page"},{"location":"pages/t001_simple_dynamics/","page":"1 Simple Dynamics","title":"1 Simple Dynamics","text":"x = SystemDynamics(rand(1); noise=ScalarNoise())\ny = SystemDynamics(rand(2); noise=DiagonalNoise(2), ρ=[1 0.3; 0.3 1])\nz = SystemDynamics(rand(3); noise=NonDiagonalNoise(2), ρ=[1 0.2; 0.2 1])\n\n# Model Dynamics","category":"page"},{"location":"pages/t001_simple_dynamics/","page":"1 Simple Dynamics","title":"1 Simple Dynamics","text":"A Model Dynamics refers to Stochastic Differential Equations that are known and fairly common in finance, such that is worth having their coefficients implemented in the library. In this case,  we need to provide the additional known parameters to the dynamics. For example, a One Factor Short Rate Model of Affine type that yields to the well known Vasicek model, can be given as:","category":"page"},{"location":"pages/t001_simple_dynamics/","page":"1 Simple Dynamics","title":"1 Simple Dynamics","text":"r0 = rand(1)\n\nϰ = 0.4363\nϑ = 0.0613\nσ = 0.1491\n\nκ(t) = ϰ\nθ(t) = ϑ\nΣ(t) = σ\n\nr = OneFactorAffineModelDynamics(r0, κ, θ, Σ, one, zero)","category":"page"},{"location":"pages/t001_simple_dynamics/","page":"1 Simple Dynamics","title":"1 Simple Dynamics","text":"group dynamics in a container","category":"page"},{"location":"pages/t001_simple_dynamics/","page":"1 Simple Dynamics","title":"1 Simple Dynamics","text":"dynamics = [:x => x, :y => y, :z => z]","category":"page"},{"location":"pages/t001_simple_dynamics/","page":"1 Simple Dynamics","title":"1 Simple Dynamics","text":"compute dynamical system","category":"page"},{"location":"pages/t001_simple_dynamics/","page":"1 Simple Dynamics","title":"1 Simple Dynamics","text":"ds = DynamicalSystem(dynamics)","category":"page"},{"location":"pages/t001_simple_dynamics/","page":"1 Simple Dynamics","title":"1 Simple Dynamics","text":"","category":"page"},{"location":"pages/t001_simple_dynamics/","page":"1 Simple Dynamics","title":"1 Simple Dynamics","text":"This page was generated using Literate.jl.","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Introduction","title":"Introduction","text":"CurrentModule = Tutorials","category":"page"},{"location":"#Tutorials","page":"Introduction","title":"Tutorials","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"Introduction","title":"Introduction","text":"","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Introduction","title":"Introduction","text":"Modules = [Tutorials]","category":"page"}]
